text: People now associate pheromones with sexual attraction, but a lot of the older pheromone research is focused on same-sex sexual suppression, e.g. urine of female mice inhibits the reproductive cycle of other females in the same cage. It's an anti-crowding mechanism to reduce...

... fertility if there's a lack of space. Older scientific publications even note similarities between these pheromones and human birth control & speculate use of birth control and intellectual concern with high population density is due to being exposed to such human pheromones.

Calcitonin is an underrated hormone, produced by the thyroid gland when serum calcium gets high, shuttles calcium/phosphate into the bones, suppresses prolactin, apparently decreases with aging. It's contained in Natural Desiccated Thyroid, but oral bioavailability is very low...
What do you think about it?
It's also a (non-direct) antagonist to parathyroid hormone which is one of the top 10 unpeatiest hormones possibly ever... Food for thought...
